ce:section.ce:para:
From the inset of Fig. 6b, the relationship between the relative fluorescence intensity ratio (F0
                        /F) of E-N-CQDs and concentrations of Fe(III) ions fitted well according to the Stern-Volmer equation, and the regression equation was obtained with a correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) of 0.993, i.e., F0/F = 0.9604 + 0.0109*CFe(III). The detection limit was calculated to be around 0.75 μmol L−1 according to the regression equation, meanwhile the signal-to-noise ratio was measured to be 3.0 (Wang et al., 2015). Atchudan et al. reported that the linear range and detection limit of the nitrogen-doped carbon dots prepared from Phyllanthus acidus was 2 − 25 μmol L−1 and 0.9 μmol L−1, respectively (Atchudan et al., 2018). Wang et al. made nitrogen-doped carbon dots from diethylene glycol using the microwave method, and they found that the linear range and detection limit of the obtained carbon dots were 1.6 − 333.3 μmol L−1 and 0.45 μmol L−1, respectively (Wang et al., 2015). In comparison with these above nitrogen-doped carbon dots, the E-N-CQDs obtained in this present work showed a relatively good detection limit. In addition, the preparation of E-N-CQDs from the EHCRs, an industrial and agricultural residues, is of both fundamental and practical importance in the strategy of preparing lignocelluloses-based CQDs.
